WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.060 --> 00:00:04.020
Well, welcome everybody. This is the Macrophages as Therapeutic

2
00:00:04.120 --> 00:00:07.080
Gatekeepers from Biology to Clinical Application session.

3
00:00:07.660 --> 00:00:11.200
I'm Jennifer Guerrero. I'm from Brigham and Women's Hospital, and I'm joined by Dr.

4
00:00:11.460 --> 00:00:14.860
Tyler Miller from Case Western Reserve University School of Medicine, and Dr.

5
00:00:14.920 --> 00:00:17.730
Tom Marron from the Tisch Cancer Institute.

6
00:00:18.500 --> 00:00:22.180
We designed this session to highlight emerging translational

7
00:00:22.320 --> 00:00:25.660
strategies to reprogram, constrain, or selectively eliminate

8
00:00:25.700 --> 00:00:29.140
immunosuppressive myeloid states to improve clinical

9
00:00:29.340 --> 00:00:32.800
outcomes. Together, these talks, we hope to

10
00:00:32.820 --> 00:00:36.680
demonstrate, will emphasize how disease-specific biology

11
00:00:36.740 --> 00:00:40.520
can inform scalable, clinically actionable myeloid targeting

12
00:00:40.580 --> 00:00:43.060
strategies. So I'm the first talk.

13
00:00:47.080 --> 00:00:48.080
Great. Thank you very much.

14
00:00:49.760 --> 00:00:53.000
And, I'm going to be talking about lipid-associated

15
00:00:53.040 --> 00:00:56.810
macrophages, their role in tumor progression,

16
00:00:56.880 --> 00:01:00.470
and novel strategies that we've developed to target these cells.

17
00:01:00.980 --> 00:01:04.280
And so a lot of this data will be unpublished, so I want to acknowledge those who

18
00:01:04.320 --> 00:01:05.820
contribute to it up front.

19
00:01:07.180 --> 00:01:10.600
My lab has spent an extensive

20
00:01:11.360 --> 00:01:15.180
amount of time trying to understand the different types of myeloid cells,

21
00:01:15.220 --> 00:01:17.980
specifically macrophages in breast tumors.

22
00:01:18.040 --> 00:01:20.000
But what we're finding is that a lot of these,

23
00:01:20.960 --> 00:01:24.700
the diversity and heterogeneity is applicable beyond just breast cancer.

24
00:01:25.580 --> 00:01:28.760
We have specifically focused on lipid-associated macrophages.

25
00:01:28.840 --> 00:01:29.740
So I'll tell you

26
00:01:30.780 --> 00:01:34.520
about one of the projects where we have identified lipid macrophages

27
00:01:35.400 --> 00:01:39.100
are responsible for therapy resistance, and we've identified

28
00:01:39.200 --> 00:01:41.860
strategies to target them clinically.

29
00:01:41.880 --> 00:01:45.750
And then in the last bit of my talk, I'll share, really for one of the first

30
00:01:45.780 --> 00:01:49.570
times publicly, a novel strategy that we've developed in which we're using

31
00:01:49.600 --> 00:01:52.760
CAR monocytes to eliminate these lipid-associated macrophages.

32
00:01:53.500 --> 00:01:57.260
So we know that macrophages are abundant across solid tumors.

33
00:01:57.280 --> 00:02:00.400
And I always like to start with this immunohistochemistry

34
00:02:01.180 --> 00:02:04.460
because I think that the visual representation is quite

35
00:02:04.560 --> 00:02:08.500
striking. So here on the left, this is normal breast tissue, on the right is a

36
00:02:08.521 --> 00:02:12.120
breast tumor. The dark brown staining indicates CD68

37
00:02:12.160 --> 00:02:15.920
positive macrophages, of which about 50% of the tumor are

38
00:02:15.960 --> 00:02:19.880
composed of these macrophages. We also know that patients who have higher

39
00:02:20.020 --> 00:02:23.880
numbers of macrophages, shown here in the green, have

40
00:02:23.920 --> 00:02:27.420
worse relapse-free survival, as well as overall survival.

41
00:02:28.440 --> 00:02:32.100
So why is that? Well, I always think about the homeostatic function of

42
00:02:32.320 --> 00:02:36.060
monocytes and macrophages. Monocytes go to sites

43
00:02:36.380 --> 00:02:36.860
of

44
00:02:38.640 --> 00:02:42.049
damage, of infection, and they facilitate repair and

45
00:02:42.100 --> 00:02:45.420
protective programs. They do the same thing in tumors.

46
00:02:45.480 --> 00:02:49.420
So cancer cells secrete factors that recruit these monocytes to

47
00:02:49.460 --> 00:02:53.440
the tumor. And when the monocytes get to the tumor, they differentiate to a

48
00:02:53.480 --> 00:02:56.960
macrophage, and they sense that there's low oxygen, poor

49
00:02:57.000 --> 00:03:00.760
nutrients, and so they become the type of cell that helps repair the

50
00:03:00.780 --> 00:03:04.640
tumor or repair these damaged cells, and in

51
00:03:04.680 --> 00:03:07.820
doing so, helps the cancer cells survive.

52
00:03:08.220 --> 00:03:11.760
These macrophages also secrete factors that lead to

53
00:03:11.769 --> 00:03:15.440
angiogenesis, metastasis. They themselves are

54
00:03:15.480 --> 00:03:17.840
impaired in their ability to present antigen.

55
00:03:18.660 --> 00:03:21.990
They recruit suppressive T regulatory cells.

56
00:03:21.990 --> 00:03:25.980
And importantly, they inhibit the recruitment and function of cytotoxic

57
00:03:26.000 --> 00:03:29.860
T lymphocytes. So given the abundance of macrophages and their

58
00:03:29.900 --> 00:03:33.840
role across solid tumors, there's been a huge

59
00:03:33.880 --> 00:03:37.820
interest in developing strategies to either inhibit these

60
00:03:37.840 --> 00:03:41.560
cells, deplete these cells, or to inhibit the things that they do, the

61
00:03:41.570 --> 00:03:42.990
suppressive factors that they make.

62
00:03:43.790 --> 00:03:47.690
And so, despite that I've spent more than a decade here, many of

63
00:03:47.720 --> 00:03:51.680
the things on this slide were, I was responsible for putting

64
00:03:51.700 --> 00:03:53.300
them on this slide, or my lab was.

65
00:03:54.120 --> 00:03:56.160
I am the first to admit it's not a home run.

66
00:03:56.560 --> 00:03:59.490
We're not curing cancer yet by targeting tumor-associated

67
00:03:59.500 --> 00:04:03.030
macrophages. And I think it's because we don't know how these drugs are really

68
00:04:03.060 --> 00:04:05.700
working. We don't know what subsets of macrophages

69
00:04:05.760 --> 00:04:09.680
these therapies are working on, and we don't know who

70
00:04:09.740 --> 00:04:11.660
is best going to benefit in what setting.

71
00:04:12.620 --> 00:04:15.800
And so, I think that this diversity

72
00:04:15.940 --> 00:04:19.079
and complexity of these cells is actually,

73
00:04:21.221 --> 00:04:25.150
if we could better understand it, we'll have better strategies to

74
00:04:25.180 --> 00:04:28.720
target them. And so this is an example of some of the

75
00:04:28.740 --> 00:04:32.690
diversity, where this is immunofluorescence on the same breast tumor,

76
00:04:33.200 --> 00:04:37.120
and five commonly used macrophage markers are shown here.

77
00:04:37.160 --> 00:04:40.020
You can see in this Venn diagram that there's very little overlap.

78
00:04:40.740 --> 00:04:44.680
So if you're talking about a CD163 positive macrophage, and I'm talking about a

79
00:04:44.720 --> 00:04:48.700
CD68 positive macrophage, we might not be talking about the same cell.

80
00:04:49.540 --> 00:04:52.760
In addition, where they're located in the tumor is important.

81
00:04:52.880 --> 00:04:54.940
Their metabolic programming is important.

82
00:04:55.440 --> 00:04:58.960
Also, their tissue specificity may be important.

83
00:04:59.260 --> 00:05:02.560
Every tissue in your body is 5% to 20% tissue-resident

84
00:05:02.620 --> 00:05:05.580
macrophages, and they have really important functions.

85
00:05:06.140 --> 00:05:09.700
The macrophages in your brain, they're involved in synaptic pruning,

86
00:05:09.780 --> 00:05:13.680
whereas macrophages in your liver or spleen are involved

87
00:05:13.720 --> 00:05:16.580
with clearing debris and other things.

88
00:05:16.640 --> 00:05:20.320
Macrophages in different tissues have

89
00:05:20.360 --> 00:05:23.320
different transcriptional, epigenetic programming.

90
00:05:23.340 --> 00:05:26.750
And so potentially, as infiltrating monocytes get to solid

91
00:05:26.780 --> 00:05:30.730
tumors, they may have different roles among the different tissues, and

92
00:05:30.760 --> 00:05:34.140
it may be something we need to consider when targeting them in different tissues.

93
00:05:35.020 --> 00:05:38.920
Okay. So we set forward to try to understand, in breast

94
00:05:38.960 --> 00:05:42.380
tumors, the diversity, the heterogeneity of

95
00:05:42.400 --> 00:05:43.260
macrophages,

96
00:05:44.220 --> 00:05:47.260
like many other groups have done across other solid tumors.

97
00:05:47.310 --> 00:05:51.260
And we had two approaches. One was to use publicly available data sets, and

98
00:05:51.300 --> 00:05:52.480
the other one is,

99
00:05:53.580 --> 00:05:56.920
we used an in-house cohort of primary

100
00:05:56.960 --> 00:06:00.469
tumors that we obtained from the Dana-Farber Brigham and Women's

101
00:06:00.820 --> 00:06:04.420
Cancer CenterAll of these samples had single-cell RNA

102
00:06:04.500 --> 00:06:07.600
sequencing, and then our cohort had a matched

103
00:06:08.980 --> 00:06:12.780
paraffin-embedded tissue that we could use for imaging and spatial analysis.

104
00:06:13.580 --> 00:06:14.540
And so to make this

105
00:06:15.540 --> 00:06:18.840
huge effort into just two short summary slides,

106
00:06:19.860 --> 00:06:23.780
we performed all the RNA sequencing, or we reanalyzed the RNA sequencing, and

107
00:06:23.800 --> 00:06:26.800
we identified multiple subsets of macrophages.

108
00:06:26.880 --> 00:06:28.780
We subclustered out the macrophages.

109
00:06:29.640 --> 00:06:33.180
We then used a number of strategies to try to understand what each subset was

110
00:06:33.200 --> 00:06:34.920
doing. So we used differential

111
00:06:36.400 --> 00:06:40.280
expression of the genes. We correlated different subsets

112
00:06:40.340 --> 00:06:43.980
of macrophages with T regulatory cells and cytotoxic T cells to try to

113
00:06:44.020 --> 00:06:47.890
understand that relationship between the different subsets of macrophages.

114
00:06:47.920 --> 00:06:49.580
We used gene set variation analysis.

115
00:06:49.640 --> 00:06:52.960
We used spatial analysis, as well as ex vivo functional studies.

116
00:06:53.700 --> 00:06:57.560
And so this is the summary of our findings, where we identified, again,

117
00:06:57.620 --> 00:06:59.970
these multiple subsets. We have common,

118
00:07:00.820 --> 00:07:04.280
the highly expressed genes are shown here on the top, and then we have these

119
00:07:04.300 --> 00:07:05.460
predicted functional

120
00:07:06.739 --> 00:07:10.360
characterizations. And so we're going to focus on two of these subsets,

121
00:07:10.660 --> 00:07:14.640
the GPNMB TAMs and this darker black box, and these SFP1

122
00:07:14.680 --> 00:07:18.410
TAMs down here. These are really the ones that emerged as being

123
00:07:18.460 --> 00:07:21.700
highly suppressive, both having signatures of lipid

124
00:07:21.740 --> 00:07:22.520
metabolism.

125
00:07:23.860 --> 00:07:27.160
And so they also were the two most abundant macrophage

126
00:07:27.260 --> 00:07:30.960
populations out of all the macrophage subsets that we could characterize

127
00:07:31.000 --> 00:07:34.980
across these breast tumors. And when we looked more closely, for example, at their

128
00:07:35.040 --> 00:07:38.940
hallmark pathway enrichment, we see that the GPNMB TAMs

129
00:07:39.000 --> 00:07:42.620
have evidence of lipid metabolism,

130
00:07:42.700 --> 00:07:46.600
fatty acid metabolism, and these SPP1 TAMs, in addition to

131
00:07:46.640 --> 00:07:49.220
lipid metabolism, they also were involved in

132
00:07:50.280 --> 00:07:54.220
hypoxia. And so you might have noticed I

133
00:07:54.240 --> 00:07:57.220
didn't use M1 or M2 at all. This is my favorite

134
00:07:57.280 --> 00:08:01.200
slide. These states don't exist. M1 is a

135
00:08:01.280 --> 00:08:05.180
LPS interferon gamma-stimulated macrophage ex vivo. Fine.

136
00:08:05.500 --> 00:08:09.210
You can say that. But in a biological setting, this is not a state that

137
00:08:09.240 --> 00:08:13.140
exists. And so I urge you to characterize your macrophages by the genes

138
00:08:13.180 --> 00:08:16.769
that they express, by the cytokines they secrete, by the predicted functional

139
00:08:16.800 --> 00:08:18.140
signatures or

140
00:08:19.360 --> 00:08:20.040
confirmed

141
00:08:21.060 --> 00:08:21.580
signatures.

142
00:08:22.900 --> 00:08:25.360
So what are these lipid-associated macrophages?

143
00:08:25.840 --> 00:08:29.420
Lipid macrophages, you can actually see lipid droplets inside of them.

144
00:08:29.880 --> 00:08:32.260
They're well described across solid tumors.

145
00:08:32.300 --> 00:08:35.691
They express TREM2, CD36, SFP1,

146
00:08:35.841 --> 00:08:38.581
APOE, both at the translational

147
00:08:39.540 --> 00:08:41.720
level and then also at the protein level.

148
00:08:42.600 --> 00:08:46.140
In normal breast tissue, I'm not sure how well this is projecting, but

149
00:08:46.500 --> 00:08:50.240
CD68 macrophages are here in red, which you can see throughout the normal

150
00:08:50.380 --> 00:08:52.760
breast tissue. Over here in the breast

151
00:08:53.940 --> 00:08:57.620
cancer, you can see this yellow, which indicates uptake of these green

152
00:08:57.680 --> 00:09:01.600
lipid droplets. So these, again, the lipid-associated

153
00:09:01.640 --> 00:09:04.020
macrophages, are well described across solid tumors,

154
00:09:04.880 --> 00:09:07.180
and they are considered highly suppressive.

155
00:09:07.240 --> 00:09:11.180
We had identified them in our single-cell analysis as having relationships

156
00:09:11.240 --> 00:09:13.560
to suppressive T cells.

157
00:09:14.720 --> 00:09:18.540
And so others have also characterized lipid-associated macrophages

158
00:09:18.600 --> 00:09:22.269
as inhibiting phagocytosis, suppressing T cells, and involved with

159
00:09:22.320 --> 00:09:23.940
migration and invasion.

160
00:09:24.820 --> 00:09:28.690
We actually had previously identified lipid-associated macrophages as

161
00:09:28.740 --> 00:09:32.640
a main driver of therapy resistance

162
00:09:32.680 --> 00:09:35.540
in BRCA-associated triple-negative breast cancer.

163
00:09:36.360 --> 00:09:40.280
So we had previously published that olaparib, which is a PARP

164
00:09:40.320 --> 00:09:43.989
inhibitor used to treat BRCA-deficient breast cancer,

165
00:09:44.840 --> 00:09:48.329
in mice induced the recruitment of highly

166
00:09:48.420 --> 00:09:49.820
suppressive lipid macrophages.

167
00:09:50.900 --> 00:09:54.640
We had this BRCA 53-deficient model of triple-negative breast

168
00:09:54.720 --> 00:09:58.500
cancer. When we treat the mice for five days, you can see that there's an

169
00:09:58.560 --> 00:10:01.900
increase in macrophages. These macrophages express

170
00:10:01.940 --> 00:10:03.900
CSF1R and PD-L1.

171
00:10:05.060 --> 00:10:08.420
When we use olaparib on healthy human donor

172
00:10:08.560 --> 00:10:12.200
CD14 positive monocytes to

173
00:10:12.240 --> 00:10:15.930
understand how PARP inhibitors may be inducing macrophage phenotype,

174
00:10:16.680 --> 00:10:20.020
we then find that as a direct effect of the PARP inhibitor,

175
00:10:20.280 --> 00:10:23.960
PD-L1 increases, but more significantly, CSF1R increases.

176
00:10:24.000 --> 00:10:27.180
Again, this is just a PARP inhibitor on a differentiating monocyte

177
00:10:27.189 --> 00:10:30.890
ex vivo. And what was

178
00:10:30.960 --> 00:10:33.400
striking is that we had performed both

179
00:10:34.420 --> 00:10:37.300
proteomics and transcriptomics, and

180
00:10:37.380 --> 00:10:41.320
overwhelmingly, the signatures that emerged to be most significantly different

181
00:10:41.340 --> 00:10:45.300
in these PARP inhibitor-treated monocytes was

182
00:10:45.340 --> 00:10:47.310
lipid metabolism-related signatures.

183
00:10:48.760 --> 00:10:51.689
And indeed, we identified that

184
00:10:51.700 --> 00:10:54.850
CD36, which is a lipid uptake receptor, is

185
00:10:55.440 --> 00:10:58.820
activated to be expressed after PARP inhibitor

186
00:10:59.080 --> 00:11:01.760
treatment. So we're using bone marrow cells from mice.

187
00:11:01.860 --> 00:11:04.880
We're differentiating to macrophages with or without olaparib.

188
00:11:05.280 --> 00:11:06.620
And the flow cytometry here,

189
00:11:07.680 --> 00:11:10.460
the vehicle-treated murine

190
00:11:11.580 --> 00:11:12.800
bone marrow is here on the left,

191
00:11:13.660 --> 00:11:15.500
and then the olaparib treated is on the right.

