00:59:45.740 --> 00:59:48.580
Thanks, Tyler. All right. Our third speaker is Dr.

1071
00:59:48.900 --> 00:59:49.740
Thomas Moran.

1072
00:59:55.248 --> 00:59:58.348
All right. Thank you to Jen and the organizers for putting this great session

1073
00:59:58.388 --> 01:00:01.948
together. I think there's obviously lots of interest in macrophages.

1074
01:00:01.988 --> 01:00:05.868
And I'm going to talk a little bit about some of the more clinical work that I'm

1075
01:00:05.888 --> 01:00:09.188
doing, that others have done to try to target some of these macrophages and some of

1076
01:00:09.228 --> 01:00:13.068
our successes and failures. Unfortunately, more failures than success so far,

1077
01:00:13.168 --> 01:00:16.868
but we're making headwinds. So I'm an immunologist initially by

1078
01:00:16.928 --> 01:00:18.848
training, and I lead the Phase one program at Sinai.

1079
01:00:18.868 --> 01:00:22.838
And my side gig is taking care of lung cancer patients, which is one of

1080
01:00:22.868 --> 01:00:25.808
my favorite days of the week, because patients these days are doing so much better

1081
01:00:25.848 --> 01:00:28.828
with the incorporation of immunotherapy into chemotherapy.

1082
01:00:28.988 --> 01:00:30.588
This is my current treatment algorithm.

1083
01:00:30.628 --> 01:00:33.658
It's based on a relatively mediocre biomarker you may have heard of called

1084
01:00:33.658 --> 01:00:37.558
PD-L1, and we're basically just giving immunotherapy with or without

1085
01:00:37.588 --> 01:00:41.448
chemotherapy. And we're more than doubling the median overall survival of these

1086
01:00:41.468 --> 01:00:45.238
patients with the incorporation of immunotherapy, which is amazing, and our clinics

1087
01:00:45.268 --> 01:00:49.168
are very happy and full. But the elephant in the room here is obviously

1088
01:00:49.208 --> 01:00:51.348
that the majority of our patients are still dying.

1089
01:00:51.388 --> 01:00:55.308
So we need to find a better way to harness the immune system to recognize and kill

1090
01:00:55.368 --> 01:00:59.048
cancer. There's really two approaches that I think are most promising.

1091
01:00:59.088 --> 01:01:01.568
Number one, really inducing vaccinal effects.

1092
01:01:01.628 --> 01:01:05.188
So on the right here, you see the incorporation of ipilimumab in

1093
01:01:05.248 --> 01:01:09.048
PD-L1 negative patients, and there we think we are seeing induction of de novo

1094
01:01:09.108 --> 01:01:13.028
clones. You can also just do neoantigen vaccines, and there's lots of RNA and

1095
01:01:13.128 --> 01:01:16.748
DNA and peptide approaches that are ongoing right now and are looking

1096
01:01:16.788 --> 01:01:20.348
promising, particularly in those patients that don't have pre-existing immunity.

1097
01:01:20.608 --> 01:01:24.098
But one of the things that we really focus on, and obviously is the focus of this

1098
01:01:24.128 --> 01:01:28.068
session, is harnessing the rest of the innate and adaptive immune system to see

1099
01:01:28.108 --> 01:01:31.708
how we can improve outcomes. Because the reality is that the vast

1100
01:01:31.748 --> 01:01:35.308
majority of the agents that we're going to be talking about here at AACR and at

1101
01:01:35.408 --> 01:01:39.268
ASCO are really myopically focused on CD8 T cells, which you can see are a

1102
01:01:39.328 --> 01:01:42.838
very small minority of immune cells within the tumor microenvironment.

1103
01:01:43.198 --> 01:01:46.868
Much more common are macrophages and neutrophils, which are pretty much ignored

1104
01:01:46.908 --> 01:01:50.688
by 99% of therapies. But we really need to

1105
01:01:51.168 --> 01:01:54.948
look outside of the CD8 compartment to see how we might be able to improve things.

1106
01:01:55.628 --> 01:01:57.608
And as Jen said, we have these good and bad.

1107
01:01:57.708 --> 01:02:01.328
I asked Gemini to make this, and she didn't even come out with an M1 and M2, which

1108
01:02:01.368 --> 01:02:05.188
was very nice. But we have the good and bad macrophages, and I think one of the

1109
01:02:05.508 --> 01:02:09.088
number one things we have to focus on and learn from our previous failures

1110
01:02:09.528 --> 01:02:11.688
is not throwing the baby out with the bathwater.

1111
01:02:11.768 --> 01:02:14.008
So not depleting both good and bad macrophages.

1112
01:02:14.048 --> 01:02:17.408
We know that macrophages are very good at killing cancer and also clearing cancer

1113
01:02:17.468 --> 01:02:21.268
debris. And so what we really need to find ways to either deplete the bad

1114
01:02:21.308 --> 01:02:25.168
macrophages or potentially repolarize these macrophages into a more

1115
01:02:25.408 --> 01:02:27.368
pro-inflammatory, anti-tumor state.

1116
01:02:27.418 --> 01:02:30.708
And that's really the goal of many of the therapies that are being developed.

1117
01:02:31.028 --> 01:02:33.848
And what we realize is we always like things to be black and white and very

1118
01:02:33.888 --> 01:02:37.878
dichotomous. The reality is that there is real spectrum of functional statuses,

1119
01:02:37.948 --> 01:02:40.368
as has been described by my colleagues here.

1120
01:02:40.588 --> 01:02:44.508
And hopefully we see lots of plasticity in the near future as we're incorporating

1121
01:02:44.548 --> 01:02:48.528
new therapies, so we can potentially move from one functional status

1122
01:02:48.568 --> 01:02:49.048
to another.

1123
01:02:50.348 --> 01:02:53.408
So there's been many approaches, and Jen very nicely

1124
01:02:54.028 --> 01:02:57.848
described an interesting approach with CSF1R blockade, and this approach has been

1125
01:02:57.908 --> 01:03:01.268
around for decades now. It just hasn't really worked.

1126
01:03:01.288 --> 01:03:04.828
And so this was one of the first studies using an anti-CSF1R.

1127
01:03:05.528 --> 01:03:09.368
This was being used in relapsed refractory solid tumors, and they did skin

1128
01:03:09.448 --> 01:03:13.068
punch biopsies to show that even from normal tissue it was very good at

1129
01:03:13.088 --> 01:03:16.868
depleting macrophages and a variety of myeloid subsets.

1130
01:03:16.908 --> 01:03:20.638
The reality, though, was that you didn't really see any significant clinical

1131
01:03:20.668 --> 01:03:24.328
efficacy there. And similarly, there's lots of small molecules that have looked at

1132
01:03:24.368 --> 01:03:28.168
inhibiting the CSF1R receptor or the CSF1 receptor.

1133
01:03:28.428 --> 01:03:31.828
This is one that was studied early on, about 10 years

1134
01:03:31.868 --> 01:03:35.108
ago. You saw very nice inhibition of the receptor

1135
01:03:35.208 --> 01:03:39.168
activation, but we saw fewer than 5% of patients actually responding

1136
01:03:39.208 --> 01:03:42.908
to this therapy. And as we move into the immunotherapy era, combining everything

1137
01:03:42.948 --> 01:03:46.918
with PD-1 blockade, this study that came out a few years ago showed that

1138
01:03:46.988 --> 01:03:50.798
a small molecule inhibitor combined with PD-1 blockade in patients that had already

1139
01:03:50.808 --> 01:03:54.128
received PD-1 blockade didn't really rescue any of the benefit there.

1140
01:03:54.788 --> 01:03:57.828
So we still have some work to go there, and I think that Jen's work really

1141
01:03:57.948 --> 01:04:00.668
highlights the need to improve the therapeutic window.

1142
01:04:00.928 --> 01:04:04.128
These drugs are somewhat toxic, so if you can really increase the

1143
01:04:04.768 --> 01:04:08.748
CSF1R on the tumor monocyte-derived macrophages you're trying to deplete, we

1144
01:04:08.788 --> 01:04:11.808
might actually finally see some benefit of these drugs.

1145
01:04:12.527 --> 01:04:15.328
Many groups have looked at blocking recruitment.

1146
01:04:15.448 --> 01:04:19.228
So we talked about how most of the monocyte-derived macrophages are being recruited

1147
01:04:19.268 --> 01:04:22.708
from the bone marrow into the blood and then through a chemokine gradient into the

1148
01:04:22.748 --> 01:04:25.528
tumor. There's many different ligands that are being

1149
01:04:26.248 --> 01:04:30.108
secreted that many of them can bind to CCR2 and

1150
01:04:30.148 --> 01:04:34.028
single cell analysis from our group of Murine lung cancer model.

1151
01:04:34.068 --> 01:04:37.648
This is KRAS mutant p53 deficient, so similar to a smoking model.

1152
01:04:38.008 --> 01:04:41.668
We see a very similar population in our smokers where we've resected tumors.

1153
01:04:42.168 --> 01:04:46.078
There's a population that we were interested in depleting that's very high in CCR2,

1154
01:04:46.108 --> 01:04:48.908
and this represents the Ly6C high monocytes.

1155
01:04:48.928 --> 01:04:52.288
These are the monocytes that are trafficking into the tumor and differentiating

1156
01:04:52.328 --> 01:04:53.948
into monocyte-derived macrophages.

1157
01:04:54.388 --> 01:04:57.988
And indeed, when you knock out CCR2, you actually see a significant

1158
01:04:58.088 --> 01:05:00.588
decrease in the growth potential of these lung tumors.

1159
01:05:01.008 --> 01:05:04.308
So this was in a very intriguing data I saw at a lab meeting, and I said, "Let's

1160
01:05:04.348 --> 01:05:07.228
plan a trial around this." We had a very nice neoadjuvant study.

1161
01:05:07.308 --> 01:05:10.898
These studies give you very big chunks of tumor that you're cutting out, so you can

1162
01:05:10.908 --> 01:05:12.828
really see if your drug is working.

1163
01:05:12.928 --> 01:05:16.228
In this study, we looked at lung and liver patients that were having their tumors

1164
01:05:16.268 --> 01:05:19.578
removed, and they just got a brief intervention of PD-1 blockade and

1165
01:05:19.608 --> 01:05:23.208
CCR2/5 inhibitor, so it blocks both those

1166
01:05:23.278 --> 01:05:23.928
chemokines.

1167
01:05:24.848 --> 01:05:28.828
And the initial data just from the CBCs, if you look

1168
01:05:28.868 --> 01:05:31.708
at the monocytes and the lymphocytes, you actually see a drop.

1169
01:05:31.768 --> 01:05:33.688
So we wanted to see a drop in the monocytes.

1170
01:05:34.008 --> 01:05:37.608
We want to see decreased efflux of these monocytes, these immature monocytes, into

1171
01:05:37.648 --> 01:05:40.908
the blood and then into the tumor. But unfortunately, I think probably because

1172
01:05:40.948 --> 01:05:44.568
there was a bit of a CCR5 inhibition, we saw a drop in the

1173
01:05:44.868 --> 01:05:46.728
lymphocyte counts in the peripheral blood.

1174
01:05:47.328 --> 01:05:50.908
And when we did single cell analysis on the resected tumors, these are very small

1175
01:05:50.968 --> 01:05:52.928
numbers, so you're not going to see anything significant here.

1176
01:05:53.238 --> 01:05:54.788
This is more hypothesis generating.

1177
01:05:54.828 --> 01:05:58.658
But one of the things we did see was a drop in the numbers

1178
01:05:58.728 --> 01:06:02.528
of Trem2 and SPP1, very immunosuppressive monocyte-derived macrophages.

1179
01:06:02.588 --> 01:06:06.478
That was the goal. The only significant thing in this very small population that

1180
01:06:06.528 --> 01:06:10.508
was depleted that were B cells. And so that's somewhat concerning because we've had

1181
01:06:10.808 --> 01:06:14.388
some papers recently that have really demonstrated the significant

1182
01:06:14.428 --> 01:06:18.388
importance of humoral immunity in response to checkpoint blockade.

1183
01:06:18.408 --> 01:06:21.428
So I think this is one example of how you can do a very small study.

1184
01:06:21.468 --> 01:06:24.928
As long as you do a deep dive, you can really see how your drug's working, and if

1185
01:06:24.948 --> 01:06:27.988
you're using it appropriately, or you should be pursuing a more rational

1186
01:06:28.068 --> 01:06:31.768
combinatorial approach. Unfortunately, I'll tell you the

1187
01:06:31.988 --> 01:06:35.448
punchline of this study that we haven't reported out yet is when you add

1188
01:06:35.488 --> 01:06:39.468
CCR2/5 inhibitor to nivolumab, it doesn't actually improve outcomes as far

1189
01:06:39.508 --> 01:06:43.138
as pathologic responses. So we would be moving on to something else.

1190
01:06:43.228 --> 01:06:46.988
So what are those other things? I think macrophages have lots of these eat me

1191
01:06:47.088 --> 01:06:50.988
signals and do not eat me signals that really dictate their functional status as

1192
01:06:51.028 --> 01:06:54.728
well as their ability to take up living or dead tumor cells.

1193
01:06:55.248 --> 01:06:59.008
And there's been many different therapies that have approached the eat me

1194
01:06:59.108 --> 01:07:02.668
and do not eat me side of this. The one that probably has the

1195
01:07:02.688 --> 01:07:05.378
most shots on goal and was the most exciting is

1196
01:07:05.408 --> 01:07:09.368
CD47. So CD47 is a do not eat me signal

1197
01:07:09.428 --> 01:07:13.258
expressed on tumor cells, and it binds to SIRPalpha on macrophages, and it

1198
01:07:13.288 --> 01:07:14.848
keeps those macrophages from eating them.

1199
01:07:14.878 --> 01:07:18.847
It basically not only blocks phagocytosis of the tumor

1200
01:07:18.888 --> 01:07:22.128
cell, it also leads to polarization of the macrophage towards a very

1201
01:07:22.188 --> 01:07:24.948
immunosuppressive tolerogenic phenotype.

1202
01:07:25.378 --> 01:07:28.188
And there was this beautiful study that came out in New England Journal.

1203
01:07:28.228 --> 01:07:29.418
This was one of the first

1204
01:07:30.368 --> 01:07:33.688
antibodies developed to bind CD47 that was put into humans.

1205
01:07:34.088 --> 01:07:37.588
This was used in patients with relapse refractory diffuse large B-cell or

1206
01:07:37.688 --> 01:07:40.948
follicular lymphoma. So all these patients had progressed on

1207
01:07:40.988 --> 01:07:44.588
rituximab, and now they were being rechallenged with rituximab, but in

1208
01:07:44.648 --> 01:07:47.848
combination with this thing that blocks a do not eat me signal.

1209
01:07:47.908 --> 01:07:50.868
So basically, you're giving an eat me signal along with a do not eat me signal.

1210
01:07:51.288 --> 01:07:55.236
And then we saw very nice responses here.One of the issues with this class of

1211
01:07:55.276 --> 01:07:58.736
therapy is that these "eat me" and "do not eat me" signals are evolutionarily

1212
01:07:58.756 --> 01:08:01.726
conserved and a very important part of your normal homeostasis.

1213
01:08:02.256 --> 01:08:05.976
There's high levels of CD47 on red blood cells, particularly older red blood

1214
01:08:05.996 --> 01:08:09.896
cells. And so a class effect of CD47 blocking antibodies, even

1215
01:08:09.916 --> 01:08:12.776
those that have been optimized somewhat, is always a bit of hemolysis.

1216
01:08:13.496 --> 01:08:16.337
Though it seems like this probably is manageable.

1217
01:08:16.396 --> 01:08:20.276
However, unfortunately, most of the development in this space has ceased, including

1218
01:08:20.316 --> 01:08:24.056
with this antibody. It was being tested in myelodysplastic syndrome as well as

1219
01:08:24.096 --> 01:08:27.956
acute myelogenous leukemia, and both those studies were negative,

1220
01:08:27.996 --> 01:08:30.896
and so this development was tabled.

1221
01:08:30.996 --> 01:08:34.196
But there are some other groups that are more intelligently looking at CD47

1222
01:08:34.236 --> 01:08:37.656
blockade with a variety of "eat me" signals like

1223
01:08:38.137 --> 01:08:41.177
FC-enabled antibodies that might be able to see some promise.

1224
01:08:41.217 --> 01:08:45.116
So hopefully we'll see some data here at AACR, and there'll be some data at ASCO

1225
01:08:45.177 --> 01:08:45.576
as well.

1226
01:08:46.616 --> 01:08:50.516
Another approach that I think is an intriguing approach is a different "do

1227
01:08:50.596 --> 01:08:54.496
not eat me" signal. That's CD24. This is also overexpressed

1228
01:08:54.516 --> 01:08:56.976
on many solid tumors, particularly after treatment.

1229
01:08:57.856 --> 01:09:01.717
And it basically binds to Siglec-10, which is expressed by macrophages

1230
01:09:01.757 --> 01:09:05.476
and both disrupts the ability of those macrophages to phagocytose cancer, but

1231
01:09:05.516 --> 01:09:09.116
also induces a very immunosuppressive functional status in those

1232
01:09:09.137 --> 01:09:13.076
macrophages. And so potentially we could block this, and indeed there is

1233
01:09:13.177 --> 01:09:15.976
a first-in-class antibody against CD24.

1234
01:09:16.516 --> 01:09:19.757
I'm actually going to be opening this trial at Mount Sinai because it's an exciting

1235
01:09:19.816 --> 01:09:23.016
approach, and they're going to be presenting some of their preclinical and early

1236
01:09:23.056 --> 01:09:26.736
clinical data on Monday, and the poster number is here, so I encourage you to check

1237
01:09:26.776 --> 01:09:27.116
it out.

1238
01:09:28.656 --> 01:09:32.536
There's many of these TAM family receptors, and these are scavenger

1239
01:09:32.596 --> 01:09:36.507
receptors that are actually an "eat me" function that

1240
01:09:36.516 --> 01:09:37.976
really turns off the macrophages.

1241
01:09:38.056 --> 01:09:41.456
So it encourages the macrophages to gobble up cell debris and really

1242
01:09:41.496 --> 01:09:45.276
induces this lipid-associated macrophage phenotype that Jen was talking about

1243
01:09:45.316 --> 01:09:45.706
earlier.

1244
01:09:46.616 --> 01:09:48.856
One of the members that this family has,

1245
01:09:49.856 --> 01:09:53.156
things like MerTK that have been extensively studied, as well as AXL.

1246
01:09:53.637 --> 01:09:55.476
I think AXL is particularly interesting.

1247
01:09:55.486 --> 01:09:59.456
This is a receptor on macrophages that binds to phosphatidylserine, which is seen

1248
01:09:59.496 --> 01:10:03.206
on dying cancer cells that are either dying because of a

1249
01:10:03.216 --> 01:10:06.476
therapeutic response or also just rapid turnover in the tumor immune

1250
01:10:06.516 --> 01:10:10.196
microenvironment. And when macrophages take up these cells through this mechanism,

1251
01:10:10.276 --> 01:10:13.296
it actually induces a very tolerogenic phenotype.

1252
01:10:13.316 --> 01:10:15.116
And so potentially we could block this.

1253
01:10:15.446 --> 01:10:17.126
And there's been many attempts to block this.

1254
01:10:17.176 --> 01:10:19.156
Unfortunately, we haven't seen much success.

1255
01:10:19.416 --> 01:10:22.556
I would say the most promising was this drug citrovatinib.

1256
01:10:22.636 --> 01:10:26.596
So this was not AXL specific, but this bound to AXL and a few

1257
01:10:26.656 --> 01:10:30.446
other. Many of these tyrosine kinase inhibitors are very dirty.

1258
01:10:31.076 --> 01:10:34.656
In this second-line study in lung cancer, I was nearly certain this was going to be

1259
01:10:34.696 --> 01:10:38.316
a positive study. We were comparing it to docetaxel, which should be a relatively

1260
01:10:38.336 --> 01:10:42.036
low bar. A combination of PD-1 blockade and this AXL inhibitor did

1261
01:10:42.096 --> 01:10:45.696
not reach statistical significance as far as improving median

1262
01:10:45.976 --> 01:10:49.616
overall survival. It is a bit of a dirtier AXL

1263
01:10:49.636 --> 01:10:53.156
inhibitor, but there are some more specific AXL inhibitors like

1264
01:10:53.176 --> 01:10:57.156
bemsetinib, which has been tested and looked somewhat promising in

1265
01:10:57.176 --> 01:11:00.996
very difficult-to-treat lung cancers, such as those who have SDK11

1266
01:11:01.036 --> 01:11:04.756
mutations. But unfortunately, those studies have also been stopped due

1267
01:11:04.836 --> 01:11:07.776
to a lack of ability to show a significant improvement.

1268
01:11:07.896 --> 01:11:10.036
So I do think that this is an interesting space.

1269
01:11:10.116 --> 01:11:13.665
I think we just need to better understand the pathway and probably the most

1270
01:11:13.756 --> 01:11:15.436
optimal combinatorial approaches.

1271
01:11:16.296 --> 01:11:19.656
So I could talk for about 18 hours about all the drugs that are being developed to

1272
01:11:19.696 --> 01:11:23.256
target macrophages, but thankfully, two of our trainees just

1273
01:11:23.536 --> 01:11:26.676
published this review in "Cancer Cell" a few weeks ago, so I highly encourage you

1274
01:11:26.716 --> 01:11:30.366
guys to check it out. They give a very nice postmortem as well as

1275
01:11:30.756 --> 01:11:33.956
a status of many of the drugs that are in development that we're trying in the

1276
01:11:33.976 --> 01:11:34.706
Phase 1 unit.

1277
01:11:36.016 --> 01:11:39.825
So, our work in the lab and our work in our Phase 1 unit is

1278
01:11:39.836 --> 01:11:43.566
really focused on understanding how we can disrupt this

1279
01:11:43.596 --> 01:11:47.236
emergency myelopoiesis. So, as was described by my colleagues,

1280
01:11:47.276 --> 01:11:50.836
there are a variety of tumor factors that are really hijacking your bone

1281
01:11:50.896 --> 01:11:54.476
marrow. They're revving up the expansion of these monocyte progenitors, the

1282
01:11:54.536 --> 01:11:56.076
granulocyte and monocyte progenitors.

1283
01:11:56.346 --> 01:11:59.596
They then also imprint on them a very immunosuppressive phenotype.

1284
01:11:59.646 --> 01:12:03.616
They then leave the bone marrow, and they traffic through a chemokine gradient into

1285
01:12:03.636 --> 01:12:07.276
the tumor microenvironment, where they differentiate into these monocyte-derived

1286
01:12:07.336 --> 01:12:11.176
macrophages. These then enable further tumor growth and metastasis, and

1287
01:12:11.196 --> 01:12:14.196
there's a very vicious cycle here, and we need to figure out how we could

1288
01:12:14.216 --> 01:12:18.036
potentially disrupt this. We've tried things like CCR2 inhibition to

1289
01:12:18.056 --> 01:12:19.516
block this. That was not effective.

1290
01:12:19.536 --> 01:12:23.476
And so one of the main focuses is understanding how, once these macrophages

1291
01:12:23.516 --> 01:12:26.986
are already really being differentiated, how we might be able to reverse that.

1292
01:12:27.016 --> 01:12:31.006
Or maybe this whole differentiation step here that's happening within

1293
01:12:31.056 --> 01:12:33.796
the tumor, how could we potentially block that as well?

1294
01:12:35.116 --> 01:12:38.836
So we've done extensive single-cell analysis on macrophages from both human

1295
01:12:39.156 --> 01:12:41.796
lesions. These are untreated non-small cell lung cancer.

1296
01:12:42.096 --> 01:12:46.016
We have similar data sets in colon cancer, in bladder cancer, and in

1297
01:12:46.086 --> 01:12:49.886
liver cancer. And we see both in lung cancer and also in this

1298
01:12:49.896 --> 01:12:53.196
preclinical model, when we're looking at their functional status, we see this very

1299
01:12:53.256 --> 01:12:56.156
strong IL-4 signaling pathway that is induced.

1300
01:12:56.556 --> 01:13:00.356
So this suggests that these cells, these monocyte-derived macrophages, have seen

1301
01:13:00.456 --> 01:13:04.296
IL-4 and that IL-4 receptor-related signaling is

1302
01:13:04.336 --> 01:13:08.176
really significantly activated in these cells and likely is doing something

1303
01:13:08.256 --> 01:13:12.016
to drive their polarization. So we found this intriguing and

1304
01:13:12.336 --> 01:13:16.256
IL-4 classically in medical school, we learn about this whole nice, once again,

1305
01:13:16.336 --> 01:13:17.816
black and white thing, which is not real.

1306
01:13:18.356 --> 01:13:20.356
But type one versus type two immunity.

1307
01:13:20.436 --> 01:13:23.896
So type one immunity, these are the good guys, antiviral, antitumor

1308
01:13:23.916 --> 01:13:27.856
responses. And type two immunity is thought to be this vestigial thing.

1309
01:13:27.976 --> 01:13:31.776
So classically, we thought of it as important for antihelminth responses.

1310
01:13:32.136 --> 01:13:34.896
We don't see a lot of helminths in New York because we use too much bleach and

1311
01:13:34.936 --> 01:13:37.716
Purell. So we do have lots of atopy, though.

1312
01:13:37.796 --> 01:13:41.296
So we cannot have bake sales in New York because everyone has horrible

1313
01:13:41.376 --> 01:13:44.936
allergies, and these atopic conditions that are very strong

1314
01:13:45.016 --> 01:13:48.996
in type two cytokines like IL-4, IL-5, IL-13, are

1315
01:13:49.076 --> 01:13:52.516
also very pro-tumorigenic. This whole pathway is very pro-tumorigenic, and it

1316
01:13:52.596 --> 01:13:56.466
overlaps with some of the functional phenotypes that we're seeing in

1317
01:13:56.496 --> 01:13:58.076
these monocyte-derived macrophages.

1318
01:13:58.586 --> 01:14:01.476
And this is not a new observation on our part.

1319
01:14:01.816 --> 01:14:05.356
Lisa Coussens, who's a former president of AACR, her lab has been working on this

1320
01:14:05.396 --> 01:14:09.316
for over a decade. They had this study that looked at blocking

1321
01:14:09.416 --> 01:14:12.916
IL-4 and combining it with classic therapies for breast cancer, which is the model

1322
01:14:12.956 --> 01:14:16.456
that she studies. And you can see here in combination with classic therapies like

1323
01:14:16.516 --> 01:14:20.276
radiation or taxane therapy, you actually see synergy, which

1324
01:14:20.336 --> 01:14:24.096
makes sense because the type two immune response is very much of a

1325
01:14:24.176 --> 01:14:28.156
healing response. So if you are causing damage with radiation or chemotherapy,

1326
01:14:28.216 --> 01:14:31.016
that's inducing this healing response, and that healing response is actually very

1327
01:14:31.036 --> 01:14:34.856
pro-tumorigenic. So potentially by disrupting this, by taking out the

1328
01:14:34.936 --> 01:14:38.828
IL-4, you might see some synergy.So we saw this data and

1329
01:14:38.848 --> 01:14:39.888
we said, "Well, that's interesting.

1330
01:14:39.948 --> 01:14:43.088
What is it going to do with PD-1?" Which is obviously how we're now treating triple

1331
01:14:43.148 --> 01:14:45.908
negative breast cancer, lung cancer, and many other solid tumors.

1332
01:14:46.448 --> 01:14:50.228
So using the KP model, which is exquisitely insensitive to

1333
01:14:50.348 --> 01:14:52.588
PD-L1, it really doesn't do anything for those

1334
01:14:53.588 --> 01:14:56.028
mice who are developing these metastatic lung cancers.

1335
01:14:56.168 --> 01:15:00.128
If you block IL-4, here using a neutralizing IL-4

1336
01:15:00.208 --> 01:15:03.708
antibody, we actually see a significant decrease in the growth potential of these

1337
01:15:03.748 --> 01:15:07.688
KP lung tumors. We have a slightly more responsive model,

1338
01:15:07.798 --> 01:15:11.038
the KP1 model, where PD-L1 does do something.

1339
01:15:11.088 --> 01:15:13.368
It does decrease the tumor growth potential.

1340
01:15:13.548 --> 01:15:16.758
You can see that it's just as good as IL-4 blockade, and if you put them together,

1341
01:15:16.828 --> 01:15:20.508
you actually appear to see some sort of immunologic synergy, really

1342
01:15:20.528 --> 01:15:22.328
significantly reducing tumor burden.

1343
01:15:23.488 --> 01:15:25.468
So I saw this data and I said, "That's super exciting.

1344
01:15:25.668 --> 01:15:29.528
How can we put that into humans?" And what we're thinking is that we

1345
01:15:29.608 --> 01:15:31.258
have this emergency myelopoiesis.

1346
01:15:31.388 --> 01:15:34.088
It's a variety of these tumor-derived factors.

1347
01:15:34.108 --> 01:15:37.878
And this is already published data, so you should take a look at this paper that

1348
01:15:37.888 --> 01:15:41.328
shows that there's really a cocktail of cytokines and chemokines that are being

1349
01:15:41.368 --> 01:15:45.088
secreted by the tumor. They're going systemically, they're hijacking your bone

1350
01:15:45.148 --> 01:15:49.108
marrow. They're activating type II granulocytes, which are actually up to 5% of

1351
01:15:49.168 --> 01:15:53.028
the cells in the bone marrow, which I didn't know until we did this study.

1352
01:15:53.248 --> 01:15:55.508
You basically are activating these type II granulocytes.

1353
01:15:55.548 --> 01:15:59.328
They're pumping out lots of IL-4. This is then imprinting the granulocyte

1354
01:15:59.368 --> 01:16:03.048
monocyte progenitor. These then expand, and then these very immature

1355
01:16:03.128 --> 01:16:06.408
immunosuppressive monocytes then traffic into the tumor

1356
01:16:06.488 --> 01:16:09.368
microenvironment. And once again, we have this very vicious cycle.

1357
01:16:09.888 --> 01:16:13.398
But nicely in preclinical models, if we use an IL-4 neutralizing

1358
01:16:13.528 --> 01:16:16.568
antibody, you can really cut this off right here in the bone marrow.

1359
01:16:16.708 --> 01:16:20.328
So the bone marrow is where all the IL-4 is being made, and using the systemic

1360
01:16:20.408 --> 01:16:24.328
IL-4 blockade or IL-4 neutralizing antibody, you cut

1361
01:16:24.388 --> 01:16:27.868
off this entire production of these monocytes and you see very nice antitumor

1362
01:16:27.878 --> 01:16:30.008
immunity in many preclinical models.

1363
01:16:30.568 --> 01:16:34.448
Thankfully, in humans, we have a drug that already has lots of safety that blocks

1364
01:16:34.528 --> 01:16:38.408
IL-4. It blocks the IL-4 receptor alpha, so disrupting both IL-4 and

1365
01:16:38.468 --> 01:16:42.258
IL-13 signaling. This has been studied in many atopic

1366
01:16:42.268 --> 01:16:46.158
conditions, including one of my pediatric colleagues at Mount Sinai gave this to

1367
01:16:46.188 --> 01:16:49.488
kids as young as one, so you know that it's a very safe drug when you're giving it

1368
01:16:49.528 --> 01:16:52.868
to a one-year-old. So I said, "Why don't we try this in patients that have lung

1369
01:16:52.908 --> 01:16:56.797
cancer who are progressing on PD-1 blockade?" So this is what I call

1370
01:16:56.848 --> 01:17:00.428
a rescue study. So basically, I have patients that have relapsed refractory

1371
01:17:00.468 --> 01:17:03.628
non-small cell lung cancer. These are patients that receive first-line

1372
01:17:03.668 --> 01:17:05.718
immunotherapy with or without chemotherapy.

1373
01:17:06.108 --> 01:17:09.968
Most of them do well initially, and then they're continued on maintenance PD-1

1374
01:17:10.028 --> 01:17:13.758
blockade, so typically pembrolizumab, or if they had stage III disease,

1375
01:17:13.828 --> 01:17:16.428
durvalumab, and they're continued on that for up to two years.

1376
01:17:16.468 --> 01:17:18.808
Unfortunately, most patients eventually start to progress.

1377
01:17:19.228 --> 01:17:22.408
So all we do here is we just continue that immune therapy that stopped working, and

1378
01:17:22.448 --> 01:17:26.028
we add on three injections of dupilumab, which binds to the

1379
01:17:26.108 --> 01:17:29.398
IL-4 receptor alpha, so blocking that type II signature.

1380
01:17:29.708 --> 01:17:33.568
We're not selecting for patients who have lots of type II immunity per se.

1381
01:17:33.768 --> 01:17:37.638
And we did biopsies before and on treatment and collected a lot of

1382
01:17:37.668 --> 01:17:41.628
blood to see how this drug was actually working in vivo in humans to see if

1383
01:17:41.648 --> 01:17:45.228
it correlated with mice. Nicely, the fourth patient we put on this trial, this was

1384
01:17:45.288 --> 01:17:46.288
a smoker who had

1385
01:17:47.648 --> 01:17:51.308
received chemoradiation. He had a very nice response initially, and then he went on

1386
01:17:51.348 --> 01:17:53.008
to immunotherapy consolidation.

1387
01:17:53.628 --> 01:17:57.068
Very soon after starting immunotherapy, he had progression not only in the initial

1388
01:17:57.228 --> 01:17:59.788
radiated tumor bed, but also in the retroperitoneum.

1389
01:18:00.128 --> 01:18:02.248
He had a very painful lesion here in his back.

1390
01:18:02.928 --> 01:18:06.468
All we did was continue immune therapy, and we added on three doses of

1391
01:18:06.488 --> 01:18:08.868
dupilumab, and the patient went into remission.

1392
01:18:09.528 --> 01:18:13.508
Basically, his pain regimen of morphine eight times a day

1393
01:18:13.568 --> 01:18:16.908
went to zero within a few weeks, so we knew that the drug was actually working.

1394
01:18:17.268 --> 01:18:20.728
And he then went on to receive two years of immunotherapy, and then he stopped, as

1395
01:18:20.788 --> 01:18:24.058
is common practice. So we had some nice responses.

1396
01:18:24.248 --> 01:18:27.178
We had these biopsies that showed that in a subset of patients, we actually were

1397
01:18:27.228 --> 01:18:30.408
inducing a de novo antitumor response.

1398
01:18:30.468 --> 01:18:34.368
We were seeing formation of tertiary lymphoid structures and nice

1399
01:18:34.408 --> 01:18:37.278
changes. And we did see about a third of patients

1400
01:18:37.968 --> 01:18:39.808
reachieve control of their disease.

1401
01:18:39.848 --> 01:18:42.488
And so these were patients where their disease had been progressing, so they

1402
01:18:42.528 --> 01:18:46.308
normally would just go on docetaxel, which is a mediocre and very toxic

1403
01:18:46.348 --> 01:18:49.928
chemotherapy. And here, a third of the patients, after we gave them those three

1404
01:18:49.948 --> 01:18:53.588
doses of dupilumab, could just continue their previous checkpoint

1405
01:18:53.608 --> 01:18:55.668
blockade, and they achieved significant benefit.

1406
01:18:55.678 --> 01:18:59.028
So we're in the process of really trying to figure out what is the biomarker that

1407
01:18:59.068 --> 01:19:02.348
identifies this subset of patients that have some sort of type II signature

1408
01:19:02.828 --> 01:19:06.228
mediated resistance, and then there's probably something else going on in the other

1409
01:19:06.268 --> 01:19:07.208
two-thirds of patients.

1410
01:19:08.108 --> 01:19:11.538
One way that we're doing that is we're exploring this in the neoadjuvant setting,

1411
01:19:11.588 --> 01:19:15.488
and so we're giving a single dose of cemiplimab, which is a PD-1 antibody

1412
01:19:15.528 --> 01:19:18.048
used in lung cancer, as well as a single dose of dupilumab.

1413
01:19:18.388 --> 01:19:21.228
And then just two weeks later, we're taking them to the operating room so we can

1414
01:19:21.268 --> 01:19:23.048
see exactly what's happening to those cells.

1415
01:19:23.068 --> 01:19:26.648
We get biopsies, and we can compare the biopsies at baseline with the tissue.

1416
01:19:26.668 --> 01:19:28.828
We're actually running this in collaboration with the SCHUM.

1417
01:19:28.908 --> 01:19:30.847
It's supported by a CRI grant.

1418
01:19:31.728 --> 01:19:35.248
So our working hypothesis of this emergency myelopoiesis is that there's these

1419
01:19:35.288 --> 01:19:36.638
tumor-derived factors that are

1420
01:19:37.508 --> 01:19:40.348
really hijacking your bone marrow, your type II granulocytes.

1421
01:19:40.388 --> 01:19:44.328
They're pumping out IL-4. They're imprinting on your myeloid progenitors that are

1422
01:19:44.348 --> 01:19:48.088
then effluxing from the marrow, trafficking to the tumor, and setting up this

1423
01:19:48.648 --> 01:19:52.268
vicious cycle. You give some dupilumab, and in a subset of patients, that

1424
01:19:52.328 --> 01:19:55.948
can disrupt this. However, like I said, two-thirds of patients are not

1425
01:19:55.988 --> 01:19:59.968
benefiting, but we know that there's a variety of other potential targets here,

1426
01:19:59.988 --> 01:20:03.178
and I told you there's a cocktail of about eight different cytokines and chemokines

1427
01:20:03.188 --> 01:20:06.788
that are coming from the tumor and leading to this effect in the bone

1428
01:20:06.808 --> 01:20:10.420
marrow.And one of the things that we saw that was part of that cocktail are

1429
01:20:10.460 --> 01:20:13.960
interleukin-1 alpha and interleukin-1 beta, and we see a very strong

1430
01:20:14.020 --> 01:20:17.480
interleukin-1 alpha and beta signature in monocyte-derived macrophages.

1431
01:20:18.100 --> 01:20:21.160
So we've been studying lung cancer in old mice.

1432
01:20:21.460 --> 01:20:25.400
They much better recapitulate the bone marrow of old humans and

1433
01:20:25.460 --> 01:20:27.540
also the lung status of old humans.

1434
01:20:27.600 --> 01:20:31.080
Nine-year-olds, thankfully, do not get lung cancer, so we shouldn't be studying

1435
01:20:31.140 --> 01:20:33.200
lung cancer in seven-week-old mice.

1436
01:20:33.620 --> 01:20:37.499
And one of the things that we did was we looked at IL-1 beta, as Tyler had said,

1437
01:20:37.800 --> 01:20:41.540
we know that this inflammasome activation really drives an immunosuppressive

1438
01:20:41.720 --> 01:20:45.620
phenotype. And anybody who hears about IL-1 beta lung cancer

1439
01:20:45.920 --> 01:20:49.740
will run out of the room because we did huge Phase III trials of canakinumab

1440
01:20:50.100 --> 01:20:53.880
once we saw a bit of a signal from a trial in cardiovascular disease called the

1441
01:20:53.940 --> 01:20:56.580
CANTOS study, and those trials were all negative.

1442
01:20:56.620 --> 01:21:00.460
The addition of IL-1 beta to standard immunotherapy did absolutely

1443
01:21:00.560 --> 01:21:04.400
nothing. Here, when we use anti-IL-1 beta, the

1444
01:21:04.440 --> 01:21:07.960
tumors grow just as poorly as they do in a control of, once again,

1445
01:21:08.029 --> 01:21:11.800
72-week-old mouse, which correlates somehow with a 65-year-old human.

1446
01:21:11.860 --> 01:21:14.220
I'm not sure of the math equation there.

1447
01:21:14.740 --> 01:21:17.660
And also we were interested in IL-1 alpha because we actually saw a stronger

1448
01:21:17.880 --> 01:21:21.420
signature of IL-1 alpha that was specific to the monocyte-derived macrophages, but

1449
01:21:21.480 --> 01:21:23.980
also IL-1 alpha blockade itself did nothing.

1450
01:21:24.000 --> 01:21:27.490
But then when Matthew, who's a superstar MD PhD student in Miriam

1451
01:21:27.500 --> 01:21:31.140
Merad's lab, she's my partner in crime, doing all these preclinical studies.

1452
01:21:31.500 --> 01:21:35.280
If you add IL-1 alpha and IL-1 beta together, we all of a sudden saw this very nice

1453
01:21:35.340 --> 01:21:39.280
signature. He had this data right around the time that we were grappling with

1454
01:21:39.300 --> 01:21:43.240
the joys of COVID in New York City and basically throwing all spaghetti at the wall

1455
01:21:43.260 --> 01:21:47.080
and seeing what stuck, and we had tried anakinra with some success in some of our

1456
01:21:47.100 --> 01:21:51.090
patients. And so we threw anakinra in these mice, and we also saw a very

1457
01:21:51.180 --> 01:21:55.120
nice anti-tumor effect. So we obviously

1458
01:21:55.140 --> 01:21:56.720
didn't want to just look at one mouse model.

1459
01:21:56.760 --> 01:21:58.820
That's always the best way not to publish something.

1460
01:21:59.220 --> 01:22:03.000
So in, once again, our old mice, we had some orthotopic models

1461
01:22:03.140 --> 01:22:06.720
of colorectal cancer with a cecal injection here

1462
01:22:06.780 --> 01:22:07.180
or

1463
01:22:08.220 --> 01:22:12.020
pancreatic cancer. And this is not a new finding that in old mice,

1464
01:22:12.200 --> 01:22:14.520
tumors grow faster, and that's very well established.

1465
01:22:14.560 --> 01:22:17.550
That's why old people get cancer, one of the reasons why old people get cancer.

1466
01:22:17.920 --> 01:22:20.780
But interestingly, we see a lot more inflammatory

1467
01:22:21.480 --> 01:22:24.320
inflammasome activation in the old mice versus the young.

1468
01:22:24.360 --> 01:22:28.349
And indeed, when we give anakinra to these old mice in this colon cancer model and

1469
01:22:28.380 --> 01:22:31.760
this pancreatic cancer model, we see a significant decrease in the growth

1470
01:22:31.820 --> 01:22:35.100
potential. So we really think that we're disrupting this

1471
01:22:35.160 --> 01:22:39.020
inflammation that occurs in the setting also of inflammaging,

1472
01:22:39.080 --> 01:22:42.300
which is just the chronic inflammation that we have over time as we age,

1473
01:22:42.360 --> 01:22:44.480
particularly living in cities like New York.

1474
01:22:44.780 --> 01:22:47.060
And we really see that we're able to disrupt this

1475
01:22:47.780 --> 01:22:50.560
inflammaging-related pro-tumorigenic milieu.

1476
01:22:52.020 --> 01:22:54.870
So based on that, we're going back to our rescue model, and we're basically just

1477
01:22:54.960 --> 01:22:58.930
adding IL-1 blockade to this. And so we're doing a trial right now

1478
01:22:58.960 --> 01:23:02.600
where we give 28 days of anakinra. This is a daily injection, which

1479
01:23:02.660 --> 01:23:06.560
is a bit of a pain for patients, but we're trying to see if we

1480
01:23:06.620 --> 01:23:09.540
can see some synergy between IL-4 and IL-1 blockade.

1481
01:23:10.600 --> 01:23:14.040
So finally, I just wanted to talk about some of the work that we're doing in a much

1482
01:23:14.080 --> 01:23:17.760
more difficult setting. I'm not sure why this is blurry, but in

1483
01:23:18.280 --> 01:23:21.700
colon cancer, microsatellite colon cancer, we know that these are patients that do

1484
01:23:21.780 --> 01:23:25.560
not respond to immunotherapy, and this is particularly true for patients with

1485
01:23:25.620 --> 01:23:29.600
colorectal mets. And so this is actually from one of our patients who had their

1486
01:23:29.640 --> 01:23:31.980
primary colon cancer removed, as well as an oligo

1487
01:23:32.860 --> 01:23:36.820
met from their liver. And you can see that in the primary tumor, there's lots of

1488
01:23:36.860 --> 01:23:40.140
CD8 T cells. The colon cancer is where we actually developed the

1489
01:23:40.180 --> 01:23:43.950
Immunoscore many decades ago, so we know that there's lots of T cells there.

1490
01:23:43.960 --> 01:23:47.780
They're just not doing their job. But in liver mets, we really see a dearth of T

1491
01:23:47.860 --> 01:23:50.980
cells, and we see a very stromal fibrotic lesion.

1492
01:23:51.390 --> 01:23:54.720
And this is one of the many reasons why we think we really don't see any response

1493
01:23:54.740 --> 01:23:58.020
in patients with liver mets. This is the study of

1494
01:23:58.300 --> 01:24:02.260
botbal, this is a souped-up CTLA-4 given with a

1495
01:24:02.300 --> 01:24:06.210
PD-1. And we've seen that in the patients with liver mets that we put on this

1496
01:24:06.220 --> 01:24:08.100
combination, we really don't see any benefit.

1497
01:24:08.640 --> 01:24:12.400
While we see a significant benefit in a subset of patients, particularly in some of

1498
01:24:12.420 --> 01:24:15.640
the neoadjuvant studies that have been running, and we're going to be updating this

1499
01:24:15.680 --> 01:24:19.500
study in the near future. So how can we overcome that very resistant

1500
01:24:19.520 --> 01:24:22.780
milieu? So the signature, this monocyte-derived macrophage

1501
01:24:22.820 --> 01:24:26.109
signature that I've been talking about and that Jen and Tyler have been talking

1502
01:24:26.180 --> 01:24:27.940
about, we really see it across tumors.

1503
01:24:28.099 --> 01:24:31.100
So we're so myopically focused oftentimes on let's develop a lung cancer

1504
01:24:31.140 --> 01:24:35.080
therapy, and we don't realize that the immune system can only be hijacked

1505
01:24:35.120 --> 01:24:38.840
in a finite number of ways. And we really think that this Type 2 signature

1506
01:24:39.060 --> 01:24:41.860
is seen in every tumor type that we've ever looked at.

1507
01:24:42.160 --> 01:24:45.870
So we initially said, "Well, let's try IL-4 blockade." And indeed, in this

1508
01:24:46.240 --> 01:24:50.180
model of metastatic colon cancer to the liver, so this is an AKPS

1509
01:24:50.220 --> 01:24:53.750
model where we inject cells into the spleen and they metastasize to the liver.

1510
01:24:54.070 --> 01:24:56.680
It's extremely insensitive to PD-1 blockade.

1511
01:24:56.700 --> 01:25:00.240
It might actually even cause some hyperprogression if you believe in that.

1512
01:25:00.440 --> 01:25:04.010
But if you give IL-4 receptor alpha blockade to these mice, you actually see a

1513
01:25:04.020 --> 01:25:07.880
significant decrease in the tumor growth, and you actually see synergy with PD-1

1514
01:25:07.920 --> 01:25:10.880
blockade, even though you didn't see any monotherapy activity here.

1515
01:25:11.220 --> 01:25:14.160
It's an important thing for investors who are always insisting on monotherapy

1516
01:25:14.220 --> 01:25:16.180
activity. Here you actually see the combination.

1517
01:25:16.800 --> 01:25:18.400
And interestingly, when we look at

1518
01:25:19.700 --> 01:25:23.620
tissue from these mice, you see that IL-4 receptor alpha blockade induces a bit

1519
01:25:23.680 --> 01:25:27.660
of an influx of immune cells, but you really see lots of these CD8 T cells

1520
01:25:27.980 --> 01:25:30.200
infiltrating when you give this cocktail of the two.

1521
01:25:30.260 --> 01:25:32.500
So we have some nice preclinical rationale.

1522
01:25:32.540 --> 01:25:35.980
And one of the interesting things was when we were looking in colon cancer in

1523
01:25:36.000 --> 01:25:39.280
humans, we have a large single-cell data set that we're going to be publishing soon

1524
01:25:39.320 --> 01:25:42.980
of human patients that had untreated colon cancer that was resected.

1525
01:25:43.310 --> 01:25:47.140
And we noticed that unlike our lung cancer patients, where monocytes that we saw

1526
01:25:47.220 --> 01:25:50.780
in the blood had already seen IL-4, had been imprinted in the bone marrow.

1527
01:25:50.820 --> 01:25:53.800
We don't see that in colon cancer patients, and we don't see that in these mice

1528
01:25:53.840 --> 01:25:56.500
that have colon cancer, either an orthotopic

1529
01:25:57.440 --> 01:26:00.320
colon cancer in their cecum or metastatic to the liver.

1530
01:26:00.360 --> 01:26:02.860
We didn't see them in the monocytes in the blood, but we see them in the

1531
01:26:02.900 --> 01:26:04.600
monocyte-derived macrophages in the tumor.

1532
01:26:04.660 --> 01:26:08.380
So it suggested maybe in this setting, the IL-4 is coming from somewhere else.

1533
01:26:08.720 --> 01:26:12.080
And indeed, with an IL-4 reporter mouse, we saw that the

1534
01:26:12.140 --> 01:26:14.040
eosinophils, there was lots of eosinophils in

1535
01:26:14.060 --> 01:26:17.870
our colon cancer patients, but particularly in this

1536
01:26:17.880 --> 01:26:21.240
preclinical model. And they were really making the vast majority of the

1537
01:26:21.320 --> 01:26:24.500
IL-4, and we see an increase in the number of eosinophils

1538
01:26:25.180 --> 01:26:29.170
in these lesions compared to a normal liver, and all those eosinophils are

1539
01:26:29.180 --> 01:26:33.100
pumping out IL-4. And doing some receptor ligand interaction, what we

1540
01:26:33.120 --> 01:26:36.520
realize is that that IL-4 probably is related to

1541
01:26:36.820 --> 01:26:40.060
fibroblast production of IL-33. So

1542
01:26:40.120 --> 01:26:43.480
IL-33 is an alarmin. There's been a few drugs recently that have

1543
01:26:44.000 --> 01:26:45.560
shown some promise in COPD.

1544
01:26:46.580 --> 01:26:49.810
Targeting IL-33, it's also a Type 2 cytokine of sorts.

1545
01:26:50.180 --> 01:26:53.660
And what we see is that in tumors, particularly the fibroblasts, are making a lot

1546
01:26:53.680 --> 01:26:57.400
of IL-33, and we know IL-33 is very good at

1547
01:26:57.660 --> 01:27:01.360
maintaining the survival and activity of eosinophils.

1548
01:27:01.370 --> 01:27:05.190
And when we look at the... This is, once again, the mouse

1549
01:27:05.280 --> 01:27:09.010
model of the liver met. We see that within the tumor, there's lots of cells that

1550
01:27:09.040 --> 01:27:12.900
are expressing IL-33, and we see that they're all these fibroblasts,

1551
01:27:12.940 --> 01:27:13.740
these stromal

1552
01:27:15.340 --> 01:27:16.660
cells surrounding the tumor cells.

1553
01:27:17.020 --> 01:27:20.400
When we look at our human samples, we also see lots of IL-33 coming from the

1554
01:27:20.420 --> 01:27:24.030
fibroblasts. And basically, our data is really showing that

1555
01:27:24.120 --> 01:27:27.770
your tumor-derived, and particularly CAF-derived IL-33,

1556
01:27:28.080 --> 01:27:31.480
is activating the eosinophils in the tumor immune microenvironment.

1557
01:27:31.600 --> 01:27:35.180
They then make IL-4 that then polarizes the monocyte-derived

1558
01:27:35.220 --> 01:27:38.900
macrophages. We can even block this whole upstream

1559
01:27:38.940 --> 01:27:41.340
signaling by using an anti-IL-1 RAP.

1560
01:27:41.500 --> 01:27:45.080
This docks out or blocks not only IL-1 alpha and beta, but also

1561
01:27:45.220 --> 01:27:48.648
ST2, the IL-33 receptor.And so here,

1562
01:27:49.348 --> 01:27:52.508
once again, in this model that doesn't respond to PD-1 blockade, if you add

1563
01:27:52.568 --> 01:27:56.528
anti-IL-1RAP, it appears to have a very nice anti-tumor effect

1564
01:27:56.568 --> 01:28:00.508
and synergize. And so we have these two different models where we block

1565
01:28:00.568 --> 01:28:03.328
IL-4 downstream or upstream. Both seem very promising.

1566
01:28:03.708 --> 01:28:07.148
So we have this trial, a platform study now ongoing, where two of the arms of the

1567
01:28:07.168 --> 01:28:10.988
platform study are looking at these cocktails in patients with colon cancer that's

1568
01:28:11.028 --> 01:28:14.848
metastasized to the liver. And we also have an oligometastasectomy trial

1569
01:28:14.888 --> 01:28:18.848
looking at the use of PD-1 and IL-4 very briefly in patients that are having

1570
01:28:19.208 --> 01:28:20.588
tumors resected from their liver.

1571
01:28:21.608 --> 01:28:24.768
So with that, thanks first and foremost to the patients who are part of these

1572
01:28:24.808 --> 01:28:27.828
studies, that spend way too much time with me and my colleagues.

1573
01:28:28.088 --> 01:28:31.688
Miriam Murad is my partner in crime, and these sorts of studies

1574
01:28:31.948 --> 01:28:34.928
literally take hundreds of people. So thank you. Happy to take questions.

1575
01:28:50.288 --> 01:28:51.768
Hi. Great talk.

1576
01:28:53.188 --> 01:28:57.088
So I was curious, this is the first I've seen eosinophils really brought

1577
01:28:57.108 --> 01:28:59.688
into the mix of the tumor microenvironment.

1578
01:28:59.748 --> 01:29:03.108
Do you expect that you would see eosinophils

1579
01:29:03.408 --> 01:29:06.068
driving this IL-4 production in other tumors as well?

1580
01:29:06.108 --> 01:29:09.868
Do you think this is specific to CRC, and do you think it's also

1581
01:29:09.908 --> 01:29:12.448
specific to MSS CRC, or

1582
01:29:13.308 --> 01:29:16.348
would you see a different immune signature in MSI where you have a lot more of

1583
01:29:16.408 --> 01:29:20.388
the mutagenic proteins?

1584
01:29:21.318 --> 01:29:24.968
So in lung cancer, we actually do not see local production of IL-4.

1585
01:29:24.988 --> 01:29:26.988
We don't see a lot of eosinophils either.

1586
01:29:27.248 --> 01:29:29.888
Eosinophilia in the blood is a very mixed bag.

1587
01:29:30.278 --> 01:29:33.388
If you look at studies correlating response to immunotherapy with

1588
01:29:33.988 --> 01:29:37.298
eosinophils, some papers say eosinophilia is a great marker for response, and

1589
01:29:37.348 --> 01:29:38.848
others say it's very immunosuppressive.

1590
01:29:39.668 --> 01:29:40.888
They're definitely a complicated cell.

1591
01:29:40.908 --> 01:29:44.068
They're a difficult cell to study, and so that's probably why we don't know enough

1592
01:29:44.128 --> 01:29:48.108
about them. Interestingly, when we look at different tumors in humans, but also

1593
01:29:48.148 --> 01:29:52.038
in the models, we see IL-4 as part of all of their stories, but it's

1594
01:29:52.068 --> 01:29:53.548
always coming from somewhere else.

1595
01:29:53.568 --> 01:29:57.228
So in ovarian cancer, we're actually seeing IL-4 being produced by ovarian cancer

1596
01:29:57.248 --> 01:30:00.298
cells themselves, and strangely, we actually see this not only in human samples,

1597
01:30:00.348 --> 01:30:03.608
but also in pre-clinical models of ovarian cancer.

1598
01:30:03.638 --> 01:30:06.668
And so I think that it's more complicated than we realize.

1599
01:30:06.708 --> 01:30:09.348
I was just telling you, we have shared immune programs throughout.

1600
01:30:09.408 --> 01:30:11.358
I think IL-4 is a shared immune program throughout.

1601
01:30:11.648 --> 01:30:14.798
It's just where the IL-4 is coming from might be different from one tumor to

1602
01:30:14.828 --> 01:30:17.008
another. It might also be different from one patient to another.

1603
01:30:17.828 --> 01:30:18.168
Thank you.

1604
01:30:22.628 --> 01:30:26.288
My question is, do you have quantified the result about

1605
01:30:26.328 --> 01:30:30.308
how many myeloid cell the human body

1606
01:30:31.048 --> 01:30:31.688
mobilized?

1607
01:30:34.268 --> 01:30:36.788
You mean in the setting of cancer, how many are being mobilized?

1608
01:30:37.028 --> 01:30:37.207
Yes.

1609
01:30:38.768 --> 01:30:42.408
I think we all showed a picture that showed that sometimes the majority of immune

1610
01:30:42.428 --> 01:30:46.078
cells in a tumor, so literally tens of billions of cells, are actually macrophages,

1611
01:30:46.448 --> 01:30:48.778
and those are primarily monocyte-derived macrophages.

1612
01:30:48.848 --> 01:30:52.608
So we see this emergency myelopoiesis, this expansion of granulocyte,

1613
01:30:52.688 --> 01:30:56.208
monocyte progenitors, really across all the tumors, and you see

1614
01:30:57.128 --> 01:31:00.628
a significant expansion compared to any sort of healthy control in the bone marrow

1615
01:31:00.648 --> 01:31:03.808
and the blood, then obviously the tumor is chock-full of these cells.

1616
01:31:03.908 --> 01:31:07.268
The half-life is a real big question. We don't know that in humans.

1617
01:31:07.328 --> 01:31:11.068
We know that they're constantly being recruited and enabling

1618
01:31:11.128 --> 01:31:14.518
tumor growth and metastasis, but we don't know how long they actually live in

1619
01:31:14.568 --> 01:31:16.568
humans. Unfortunately, that's very difficult to track.

1620
01:31:16.608 --> 01:31:20.448
So we don't know, are they turning over once a week, every 72 hours, or are they

1621
01:31:20.568 --> 01:31:24.048
sticking around for a few months? So how great is that

1622
01:31:24.088 --> 01:31:27.088
recruitment? And that's an important question if we're thinking about finding ways

1623
01:31:27.128 --> 01:31:29.008
to block recruitment, for sure.

1624
01:31:30.468 --> 01:31:33.568
Actually, my question, it also has a specific setting.

1625
01:31:33.608 --> 01:31:37.328
It's the cancer patient after the treatment, after chemo

1626
01:31:37.528 --> 01:31:40.948
or radiation treatment, and how much the

1627
01:31:41.408 --> 01:31:45.248
bone marrow mobilize the myeloid immune cell get into the

1628
01:31:45.288 --> 01:31:47.168
tumor. Do you have estimation?

1629
01:31:47.548 --> 01:31:49.828
No. I don't have specific data on that.

1630
01:31:49.928 --> 01:31:53.588
I think that we know that the tumor is releasing all these factors, so as you kill

1631
01:31:53.668 --> 01:31:56.858
off tumor with radiation and chemotherapy, you could argue you're going to have

1632
01:31:56.868 --> 01:32:00.158
fewer cancer cells and fewer stromal cells pumping out those cytokines and leading

1633
01:32:00.188 --> 01:32:03.538
to expansion in the bone marrow. But also, as part of this healing

1634
01:32:03.568 --> 01:32:07.288
response to those very toxic insults, that might actually do the

1635
01:32:07.367 --> 01:32:10.278
